    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1964-06-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1964-06-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="223"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d223">
                <head>223. Memorandum for the Record<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d223fn1"
                        >Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Subject File,
                        Trade—General, Vol. I [1 of 2], Box 47. No classification marking. Prepared
                        by <persName corresp="#p_BFM1">Francis M. Bator</persName>. An attached note
                        from <persName corresp="#p_BFM1">Bator</persName> to <persName
                            corresp="#p_BMG2">McGeorge Bundy</persName>, dated June 11, reads: “Mac:
                        I have checked this with <persName corresp="#p_MCS1">Murphy</persName> and
                            <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>’s man, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NS7">Nehmer</persName>. They are content.” A further
                        handwritten note by <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">Buddy</persName> reads:
                        “Good work. Told D. Walker, 6/12/64.” <persName corresp="#p_BFM1"
                            >Bator</persName>’s typed notes, June 11, which he apparently drafted in
                        preparation for this meeting, are ibid.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1964-06-11">June 11, 1964</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Extra Long Staple Cotton—Meeting, Thursday, June 11, 1964—Situation Room,
                        White House</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PRESENT</head>
                    <item>White House—<persName corresp="#p_BMG2">Buddy</persName>, Feldman,
                        Brubeck, <persName corresp="#p_BFM1">Bator</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>State—<persName corresp="#p_JGG1">G.G. Johnson</persName>, Grant, Adams,
                            <persName corresp="#p_NS7">Nehmer</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Agriculture—<persName corresp="#p_MCS1">Murphy</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_STR1">STR</gloss>—<persName corresp="#p_RWM2"
                            >Roth</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>CEA—<persName corresp="#p_AHG1">Ackley</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>B.O.B.—Capron, <persName corresp="#p_SCL1">Schultze</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>It was agreed that: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Agriculture will attempt to speed up the export of <hi rend="italic"
                                >foreign produced</hi>
                            <gloss target="#t_ELS1">ELS</gloss>, taking care, however, not to drive
                            down the world price appreciably below its present level. (We shall know
                            more about the prospects, and Agriculture will consult with State, after
                            next week’s bids are in.)</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Agriculture, State and B.O.B. will explore the possibility of
                            disposing of <gloss target="#t_ELS1">ELS</gloss> stock under <gloss
                                target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Messrs. <persName corresp="#p_MCS1">Murphy</persName> and Feldman are
                            at liberty to tell the U.S. parties at interest that (a) the foreign
                            stock will be sold at an accelerated rate—subject to the proviso about
                            price; (b) subject to the state of the market, an export program for <hi
                                rend="italic">domestic</hi>
                            <gloss target="#t_ELS1">ELS</gloss> will almost certainly be undertaken
                            with, however, no bids to be accepted at less than the 49 cent domestic
                            support price. About the possibility of exporting domestic at <hi
                                rend="italic">less</hi> than the support price, they are to be
                            noncommittal and avoid raising people’s hopes.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>State is to warn its clients that we do expect to reduce our <gloss
                                target="#t_ELS1">ELS</gloss> stock at the fastest rate possible
                            without breaking the market but that we do not, as of now, plan to sell
                                <hi rend="italic">domestic</hi> at less than the current U.S.
                            support price. It should be made clear, however, that as regards the
                            future, no one can be certain.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BFM1">
                            <hi rend="strong">FMB</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
